content.description: Start in the cave at a jug and move out over the roof to the regular start.
This traverses the left side of the roof. Start from jugs on the left and traverse right, finishing with a crack.
content.protection: Pad and someone to move it along under you.

content.description:
Its been a long time so it is a bit fuzzy but.....

Stand start by any means to get onto the face above the chest high roof. Trend up and right via nice face climbing. Gain a nice muffin on the lip/arete. Mantle onto the slab and top out.
content.location: In between the notch on the approach and the cave itself.

content.description: This problem is a super classic, and perhaps the best problem of its grade in Joshua Tree. Essentially Caveman's big, secluded brother. Climb the sustained roof on jams, edges and heel hooks with a dynamic finish on sloper slapping. Some trickery allows you to completely recover before launching into the final sequence. The plastic-trained climber who loves gymnastic moves on relatively large holds will adore this one.
content.protection: A single pad will suffice, but have a spotter who can drag it as you climb. If you're solo and at your limit two pads would be nice.
content.location: At the far right side of Alister's Cave is a chalked jug and overhead handjam slot. Sit start and work through the roof ending at obvious jugs in a break just above the dismal finishing slopers.
